    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>Why Your Daily Total Is Only Half the Story</h2>

    <p>Here's a scenario that plays out in thousands of men's lives every day: a 200lb man hits 120g of protein. Good total. Solid effort. And yet he spent 18 of the past 24 hours in a catabolic state — muscles slowly breaking down — because of how that 120g was distributed.</p>

    <p>The biology is straightforward but rarely discussed: muscle protein synthesis is not a function of your daily protein total. It's triggered meal by meal, each time you clear the leucine threshold — the amino acid concentration required to activate the mTOR signaling pathway that initiates muscle repair and growth. After 40, that threshold rises due to <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a>, and a meal that would have been adequate at 30 may need to be closer to 35–40g to generate a full response.</p>

    <p>What this means in practice: a light breakfast, a moderate lunch, a small snack, and a protein-heavy dinner might add up to 120g — but only the dinner crossed the threshold. You had one anabolic window in a 16-hour waking day.</p>

