        <span>120g total · <span class="tl-windows">1 of 4 meals anabolic</span></span>
        <span>18 hours catabolic</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>That one anabolic window — triggered by a large dinner — is doing all the muscle-building work for the day. The other 18 waking hours, your body is in net breakdown mode. This is the protein back-loading trap, and it's where most men over 40 unknowingly live.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 2 — THE SCIENCE -->
    <h2>What the Research Shows About Protein Distribution</h2>

    <div class="science-box">
      <h3>The Distribution Evidence</h3>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>The 25% Distribution Advantage.</strong> A landmark 2014 study in the Journal of Nutrition by Mamerow et al. compared two groups eating identical daily protein totals. The group that distributed protein evenly across three meals stimulated muscle protein synthesis approximately 25% more than the group that ate the same total unevenly. Same grams. Dramatically different results.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>The 4–5 Hour Window.</strong> Research from Dr. Donald Layman at the University of Illinois established that each muscle protein synthesis episode lasts approximately 4–5 hours following a threshold protein dose. This is your anabolic window — after it closes, the next meal needs to re-trigger it. Eating all your protein in one meal doesn't extend the window; it wastes the opportunity.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>The 40+ Threshold Shift.</strong> Multiple studies, including work from Dr. Stuart Phillips at McMaster University, confirm that anabolic resistance in older adults raises the per-meal protein threshold. Where a 25-year-old might get a full MPS response from 20–25g, a man over 40 typically needs 30–40g per meal to achieve the same signal. The math of pacing matters more, not less, as you age.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-dot"></div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>The "Muscle Full" Effect.</strong> Research also shows a ceiling: consuming more than 40–50g of protein at a single sitting does not proportionally increase muscle protein synthesis — the muscle becomes "full" and the excess is oxidized for energy. This is why one massive protein meal cannot compensate for three catabolic ones.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 3 — THE FIX -->
