    <p style="margin-top: 24px;">Four anabolic windows. Every meal crossing the threshold. The same waking hours that were previously catabolic are now working for you. This is the entire shift — not eating more, but distributing what you eat so it actually triggers muscle building every time.</p>

    <!-- THREE RULES -->
    <h2>The Three Rules of Protein Pacing</h2>

    <div class="protocol-grid">
      <div class="protocol-card">
        <div class="pc-num">30g+</div>
        <h4>Every Meal Clears the Threshold</h4>
        <p>No meal should fall below 30g. Below that line, the leucine signal isn't strong enough to trigger meaningful muscle protein synthesis after 40. A 20g meal isn't "partial credit" — it's a missed window.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="protocol-card">
        <div class="pc-num">4–5h</div>
        <h4>Space Meals to Renew the Signal</h4>
        <p>Each anabolic window lasts 4–5 hours. Eating protein again before the window closes doesn't extend it — it wastes it. Space meals 4–5 hours apart to generate a fresh stimulus each time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="protocol-card">
        <div class="pc-num">≤50g</div>
        <h4>Don't Overshoot Any Single Meal</h4>
        <p>Research shows MPS hits a ceiling around 40–50g per meal. Eating 80g at dinner doesn't give you double the signal. It gives you roughly the same signal as 40g — and wastes 40g of protein as fuel.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- THE BREAKFAST PROBLEM -->
    <h2>Why Breakfast Is the Biggest Leverage Point</h2>

    <p>For most men, the largest catabolic gap in the day isn't between lunch and dinner — it's from the moment you wake up. After 8+ hours of fasting overnight, your body is already in a profoundly catabolic state. A weak 2-egg breakfast at 15–20g doesn't flip the switch. You are literally cannibalizing your own muscle tissue until noon or later — when you finally eat a meal that actually clears the threshold.</p>

    <p>That's 14–16 hours of uninterrupted net muscle breakdown before you've even triggered a single anabolic window. And it happens every day you let breakfast stay light.</p>

    <p>The highest-leverage single change most men can make is front-loading the day with protein. Not adding a protein shake at midnight. Not eating more at dinner. Getting 40–50g at the first meal closes the overnight catabolic gap and sets the rhythm for everything that follows.</p>

