    <!-- THE TRACKING POINT -->
    <h2>Why This Is Impossible to Do by Feel</h2>

    <p>Here's the honest truth about protein pacing: it requires knowing your per-meal number, not just your daily number. And knowing your per-meal number requires tracking it — at least until the pattern becomes automatic.</p>

    <p>Most men who start tracking discover their distribution problem within three days. They assumed breakfast was "pretty good." It was 18g. They assumed their afternoon snack was "adding up." It was 8g. Two meals they thought were contributing were actually costing them anabolic windows every single day.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">The Feel Test Fails Here</div>
      <p>You cannot feel the difference between 22g and 32g at a meal. The leucine threshold is not something your body communicates clearly. A meal that misses the threshold doesn't feel different from one that hits it — but the downstream muscle-building effect is completely different. This is precisely where visibility matters most.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The fix isn't complicated. Track your protein meal by meal for one week. You'll see your distribution pattern immediately. You'll know exactly which meal is your weakest link. And you'll know exactly what to adjust — usually just one or two meals — to flip those windows from catabolic to anabolic.</p>

    <p>The <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/is-100g-protein-enough-200lb-man/">100g post shows the per-meal math</a> for a 200lb man in detail. The pattern almost always reveals the same thing: breakfast and the afternoon snack are the two catabolic weak points. Fix those and the whole day restructures.</p>

