    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is protein pacing?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Protein pacing is distributing your daily protein intake across 3–4 meals, each hitting at least 30g, rather than back-loading most of it at dinner. The goal is to maximize the number of anabolic windows — muscle protein synthesis episodes — you trigger throughout the day. Research shows even distribution produces about 25% more muscle protein synthesis than the same total eaten unevenly.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should men over 40 eat protein to build muscle?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research supports protein-rich meals every 4–5 hours, with each meal hitting at least 30g. For men over 40, this typically means 3–4 meals per day built around a protein anchor. Each anabolic window lasts about 4–5 hours — after it closes, a new meal needs to re-trigger it. Eating more protein before the window closes doesn't extend it.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is it better to spread protein throughout the day or eat it all at once?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Spreading protein evenly is significantly more effective for muscle preservation after 40. A 2014 Journal of Nutrition study found even distribution stimulated muscle protein synthesis roughly 25% more than the same total consumed unevenly. Each meal triggers MPS independently — a large dinner cannot compensate for three catabolic meals earlier in the day.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What does it mean to be catabolic vs anabolic?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Anabolic means your body is in a muscle-building state — triggered when a meal provides 30g+ of protein to activate muscle protein synthesis via the mTOR pathway. Catabolic means your body is in net muscle breakdown — what happens when meals are too low in protein to cross the synthesis threshold. After 40, anabolic resistance raises that threshold, making per-meal dosing more critical.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How many grams of protein per meal to stay anabolic after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research consistently points to 30g per meal as the minimum threshold for meaningful muscle protein synthesis in men over 40, with some studies suggesting 40g is more effective given anabolic resistance. Meals below 30g fail to adequately trigger muscle building regardless of your daily total — they are effectively catabolic meals from a muscle-preservation standpoint.</div>
      </div>
